bols, each corresponding to one path; in addition, each card shows a number (0-10, twice each). In each color, each player can play his cards in either ascending or descending order. As in Lost Cities, it's better to concentrate on a few paths since the final spaces on a path grant high points, but ending early gives negative ones.<br/><br/>The active player plays one card (out of a hand of eight) or discards one, then moves the corresponding playing piece on the path. Many of the spaces have a token that grants some bonus: either immediate points (counted on the scoring track), an extra move on a path, or wishing stones that are needed at game end to avoid negative points.<br/><br/>The game ends when five playing pieces (from any combination of players) have reached the seventh (or higher) space on their respective paths. Now, scoring happens: <br/><br/>     Pieces that moved only 1-3 steps earn negative points (-4, -3, -2).<br/>     Pieces with 4+ steps earn points (1, 2, 3, 6, 7, 10). <br/>     One piece of each player twice the height of other pieces scores double, either positive or negative. <br/>     Holding fewer than two wish stones earns negative points (-3 / -4), while a collection of five or more stones yields a bonus of 10 points.<br/><br/><br/>All endgame points are added to any scored during the game. The player with the highest score wins!<br/><br/><br/>Primary differences between Lost Cities: The Board Game and Keltis:<br/><br/>1. In LCBG you play 3 rounds, scoring at the end of all 3 for the monuments you collect. (Normal scoring occurs each round.) In Keltis, you only play 1 round, and score everything each round. This is not just a rule difference, as the scoring is different for the monuments/stones based on the number collected.<br/><br/>2. In Keltis, you may play your cards in either order, high to low, or low to high. In LCBG, you must go low to high.<br/><br/>Note: the rules for LCBG have the Keltis rules as variants, and have the board elements necessary for #1 above. Keltis does not have the rules nor board elements to play LCBG.<br/><br/>There are more differences that are non-substantive. (Art, points in LCBG multiplied by 5, etc.)<br/><br/>"]} {:tag :thumbnail, :attrs nil, :content ["https://cf.geekdo-images.com/GnKS0zE-EkuYfCrEUIlfzA__thumb/img/7qofFSLH0zgMMtQFcqxfiwDM-xg=/fit-in/200x150/filters:strip_icc()/pic382457.jpg"]} {:tag :image, :attrs nil, :content ["https://cf.geekdo-images.com/GnKS0zE-EkuYfCrEUIlfzA__original/img/7W0n_8AgNak7XBEJ5r7gNZLFuWY=/0x0/filters:format(jpeg)/pic382457.jpg"]} {:tag :boardgamepublisher, :attrs {:objectid "37"}, :content ["KOSMOS"]} {:tag :boardgamehonor, :attrs {:objectid "19016"}, :content ["2008 Japan Boardgame Prize Voters' Selection Nominee"]} {:tag :boardgamehonor, :attrs {:objectid "8638"}, :content ["2008 Spiel des Jahres Nominee"]} {:tag :boardgamehonor, :attrs {:objectid "8637"}, :content ["2008 Spiel des Jahres Winner"]} {:tag :boardgamehonor, :attrs {:objectid "9281"}, :content ["2009 Årets Spill Best Family Game Nominee"]} {:tag :boardgamehonor, :attrs {:objectid "8413"}, :content ["2009 Golden Geek Best Family Board Game Nominee"]} {:tag :boardgamehonor, :attrs {:objectid "21193"}, :content ["2009 Gouden Ludo Nominee"]} {:tag :boardgamehonor, :attrs {:objectid "24464"}, :content ["2011 Hungarian Board Game Award Nominee"]} {:tag :boardgamepublisher, :attrs {:objectid "267"}, :content ["999 Games"]} {:tag :boardgameversion, :attrs {:objectid "80792"}, :content ["Chinese edition"]} {:tag :boardgamepublisher, :attrs {:objectid "4335"}, :content ["Competo / Marektoy"]} {:tag :boardgamepublisher, :attrs {:objectid "2366"}, :content ["Devir"]} {:tag :boardgameversion, :attrs {:objectid "25016"}, :content ["Dutch edition"]} {:tag :boardgamepodcastepisode, :attrs {:objectid "182502"}, :content ["Ep 035 – Spiel des Jahres predictions and discussion"]} {:tag :boardgamepodcastepisode, :attrs {:objectid "11830"}, :content ["Episode 16: Keltis"]} {:tag :boardgam